Message Passing Interface for Python

Pradeep Niroula | Sat 22 August 2020

For the first simulation I ever ran on a computing cluster, I used a small wrapper to distribute my code to multiple processors using the Message Passing Interface. This technique has stuck with me because it is so simple. The kind of simulations I typically run do not need a lot of memory but involves running a small, tedius job many many times to get an ensemble average. My simple MPI construction is perfect for such simulations.

Message Passing Interface¶

My understanding of Message Passing Interfaces is as rudimentary as it gets. If you run a simulation distributed over $N$ processors, one of the processors is designated to be the Controller. The Controller does distributes little pieces of work (jobs) to all other processors and does the bookkeeping (ie compiling results from them).

The Controller scatters jobs across available processors. And it collects results from them once the job is completed.

Finally, the controller also compiles results from each processor to produec the final output.

MPI Wrapper for Python¶

I wrote a tiny wrapper that could be useful to those beginning on MPI. My starter code is on [github].(https://github.com/npdeep/mpi4py-starter)

For this starter, I conceive of a job (or an experiment as I call it) where each processor samples $N$ samples from the normal distribution $\mathcal{N}(\mu, \sigma^2)$ and returns the mean and standard deviation of the square of the observations.

$$ \text{Return: }\mathbb{E}(Y), \text{Var}(Y)^{1/2} \quad Y = X^2 \qquad \text{ where } X \sim \mathcal{N}(\mu, \sigma^2) $$

The experiment or job run by each processor looks like this:

def simulate(params: SimulationParams):
    samples = np.random.normal(params.mean, params.std, params.n)
    samples_sq = np.square(samples)
    return np.mean(samples_sq), np.std(samples_sq)

SimulationParams is just a class to hold the parameters of the simulation. In our case, the parameters are $\mu, \sigma$ for $X$ and the number of samples to be taken.

class SimulationParams:
    def __init__(self, mean, std, n):
        self.mean = mean
        self.std = std
        self.n = n

The main wrapper uses an if statement to separate the work of a controller and work of a child process.

from mpi4py import MPI
comm = MPI.COMM_WORLD;

def main():
   if comm.rank == 0:
        % the job of a controller

    else:
        % job of a child process

The controller's job includes

  • making a list of all the jobs that need to be done
  • scattering the jobs across all processors
  • compiling the results 
if comm.rank == 0:
    # run the experiment for many values of mu and sigma
    mean_s = np.linspace(0, 10, 5)
    std_s = np.linspace(0, 10, 5)
    n = 1000   # number of samples to take in each simultion

    # create a list for simulation params
    params_list = []
    for mean in mean_s:
        for std in std_s:
            params = SimulationParams(mean, std, n)
            params_list.append(params)

    # prepare to send the parameters to processes as jobs.
    # comm.size = Number of processes.
    # create a list of jobs for each process.
    jobs_list = [[] for _ in range(comm.size)]
    for k, params in enumerate(params_list):
        # distribute the jobs to all the processes evenly.
        jobs_list[k % comm.size].append(params)
else:
    # The child worker doesn't get to assign jobs.
    jobs_list = None

After both the controller and child processes make a list of jobs (for the child process, the joblist is just empy). The controller and child process both send their respective list of jobs to other processors.

my_work = comm.scatter(jobs_list)
my_result = child_worker_job(my_work)
result_chunks = comm.gather(my_result)

Finally, the controller collects the results from all the child processors and compiles them. In our case, we write all the results to a file.

if comm.rank == 0:
    """
    Process the result
    """
    data = []
    for result_chunk in result_chunks:
        for result in result_chunk:
            # the first element is the simulation parameters we had transmitted earlier
            params = result[0]
            input_mean = params.mean
            input_std = params.std

            output_mean, output_std = result[1]

            data.append((input_mean, input_std, output_mean, output_std))

    # process the data as you like or write it to a file
    with open("simulation_data.txt", "w") as output_file:
        for row in data:
            output_file.write(str(row) + "\n")

Again, the code is on github. Hope someone finds it useful.
